{
  "title": "Optimizing Web Backends with FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide explains how to optimize web backends using the FastAPI framework in Python 3.12+, focusing on best practices and features that enhance performance.",

  "key_points": [
    "Use of asynchronous functions and middleware for handling concurrent requests efficiently",
    "Leverage caching to reduce database calls and improve response times",
    "Implementing HTTP/2 server push for faster delivery of static assets",
    "Using FastAPI's built-in features like automatic documentation generation, openapi validation, and type hints for writing cleaner and more maintainable code",
    "Leveraging FastAPI's built-in rate limiting to prevent overloading the server with excessive requests"
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI, Cache\napp = FastAPI()\ncache = Cache(backing_store='memory', expiration=60)\ndef get_item(id: int):\n    @app.get('/items/{id}')\n    async def get_item_handler(id: int):\n        item = cache.get(id) \n        if item is None:\n            item = some_function_to_fetch_item(id)\n            cache[id] = item\n        return item"
    },
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "from fastapi.middleware.http2 import HTTP2ServerPushMiddleware\napp = FastAPI()\napp.add_middleware(HTTP2ServerPushMiddleware, path='/', handle_push=lambda req: [{\"path\": '/styles.css'}])"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "FastAPI version 0.71.0 and above supports Python 3.12",
    "Some of the mentioned features might not be available in earlier versions; please check the FastAPI documentation for feature availability"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While asynchronous functions can greatly improve performance, misuse can lead to increased memory consumption and other issues",
    "Ensure caching is used judiciously as it can potentially lead to stale data if not properly implemented with appropriate expiration or invalidation strategies"
  ]
}
